JOHANNESBURG – New banknotes commemorating what would have been a centenary year for former state head Nelson Mandela will be launched this year, the South African Reserve Bank (SARB) said on Sunday. “The notes will cover all dominations from R10, R20, R50, R100 and R200,” the country’s central bank said in a statement. “At the same time, the South African Mint, a subsidiary of the SARB will issue a new R5 circulation coin celebrating Mandela’s birth centenary.” READ: Nationalising Reserve Bank will be expensive: SARB It said that the existing Mandela bank notes and R5 coin in circulation will remain legal tender and will continue to be issued. The new banknotes are expected to be introduced into circulation from July 18, a date in which Mandela was born but no further details were said. SARB Commemorates Nelson Mandela's Birth Centenary by eNCA.com on Scribd “Nelson Mandela represented the best version of ourselves as South Africans… while preserving the value of money is our main mandate, our purpose is to be a bastion of institutional strength, contributing to a stable and prosperous economy that serves the well-being of all South Africans and guided in part by Madiba’s values said SARB Governor Lesetja Kganyago. eNCA